00:40:11.350 --> 00:40:14.240
delivering information but to
inspire them, to actually make

00:40:14.240 --> 00:40:16.340
them interested in
the subject.

00:40:16.340 --> 00:40:22.220
How do you envision your work
helping them do that?

00:40:22.220 --> 00:40:24.520
SALMAN KHAN: There's a couple
of dimensions here.

00:40:24.520 --> 00:40:26.710
On the simplest dimension, what
we saw a Los Altos even

00:40:26.710 --> 00:40:29.270
two years ago, is we did
it just by giving them

00:40:29.270 --> 00:40:30.770
the room to do it.

00:40:30.770 --> 00:40:32.620
You take that lecture
out of the room.

00:40:32.620 --> 00:40:35.780
And you actually take a lot of
the administration out of the

00:40:35.780 --> 00:40:37.650
room in terms of grading
homework.

00:40:37.650 --> 00:40:39.370
And you take that out of the
room, Now&gt; all of the sudden,

00:40:39.370 --> 00:40:42.300
the teacher has what they want
to do with the classroom.

00:40:42.300 --> 00:40:45.320
And some of those teachers
that we worked with were

00:40:45.320 --> 00:40:45.840
incredible.

00:40:45.840 --> 00:40:47.960
They had a list of things that
they really wanted to do.

00:40:47.960 --> 00:40:49.070
They were doing these
really interesting

00:40:49.070 --> 00:40:50.740
projects that were inspiring.

00:40:50.740 --> 00:40:53.240
They were like, for the first
time, I'm able to spend some

00:40:53.240 --> 00:40:54.750
time with every student
in the classroom.

00:40:54.750 --> 00:40:57.470
Literally, just talking to
someone on a personal level is

00:40:57.470 --> 00:41:00.610
inspiring them, as opposed to
being distant from them.

00:41:00.610 --> 00:41:02.190
But on top of that,
we do realize--

00:41:02.190 --> 00:41:03.770
we've been saying, class
time should be used for

00:41:03.770 --> 00:41:04.025
interaction.

00:41:04.025 --> 00:41:06.090
It should be used
for projects.

00:41:06.090 --> 00:41:08.170
Projects are not a
trivial thing.

00:41:08.170 --> 00:41:11.230
It's very easy to have bad
projects, cookbook projects.

00:41:11.230 --> 00:41:14.750
And so that's why we wanted
to put resources into this

00:41:14.750 --> 00:41:15.540
computer science.

00:41:15.540 --> 00:41:17.050
Because it's so general.

00:41:17.050 --> 00:41:18.120
It can be used in anything.

00:41:18.120 --> 00:41:19.660
I just made a video for--

00:41:19.660 --> 00:41:21.450
LeBron James literally reached
out and said, I want to help

00:41:21.450 --> 00:41:24.320
make math videos.

00:41:24.320 --> 00:41:25.720
ERIC SCHMIDT: This
never happens.

00:41:25.720 --> 00:41:27.296
SALMAN KHAN: This
never happens.

00:41:27.296 --> 00:41:28.195
ERIC SCHMIDT: It's
like the fifth

00:41:28.195 --> 00:41:28.940
thing that never happens.

00:41:28.940 --> 00:41:30.330
SALMAN KHAN: This is the fifth
thing that never happens.

00:41:30.330 --> 00:41:30.870
ERIC SCHMIDT: Did he call you?

00:41:30.870 --> 00:41:31.760
Or did you call him?

00:41:31.760 --> 00:41:33.410
SALMAN KHAN: No, he called us.

00:41:33.410 --> 00:41:35.423
I mean, his people
called my people.

00:41:35.423 --> 00:41:40.560
[LAUGHTER]

00:41:40.560 --> 00:41:44.030
SALMAN KHAN: But he asked these
interesting questions

00:41:44.030 --> 00:41:44.460
related to math.

00:41:44.460 --> 00:41:48.500
One of them is, you have 30
seconds left, down by three.

00:41:48.500 --> 00:41:52.640
Is it better to shoot the three
or take the two, foul,

00:41:52.640 --> 00:41:54.850
hope for another possession?

00:41:54.850 --> 00:41:56.540
ERIC SCHMIDT: These are problems
that have occupied

00:41:56.540 --> 00:41:56.980
him for some time.

00:41:56.980 --> 00:42:00.440
SALMAN KHAN: Well, it
a core problem.

00:42:00.440 --> 00:42:02.270
And it's funny.

00:42:02.270 --> 00:42:03.370
Because at first, I was
like, I'm going to

00:42:03.370 --> 00:42:04.240
make a video for it.

00:42:04.240 --> 00:42:07.080
And I started doing a decision
tree for it.

00:42:07.080 --> 00:42:08.840
And actually, there's a second
scenario that gets quite

00:42:08.840 --> 00:42:10.670
complicated, based on the
did they make one free--

00:42:10.670 --> 00:42:12.530
how much time went off the
clock, and all that.

00:42:12.530 --> 00:42:14.780
I said, I have this great
computer science tool now.

00:42:14.780 --> 00:42:18.930
So I did a Monte Carlo
simulation, for LeBron James.

00:42:18.930 --> 00:42:20.620
ERIC SCHMIDT: This has
also never happened.

00:42:20.620 --> 00:42:23.470
SALMAN KHAN: This has
also never happened.

00:42:23.470 --> 00:42:24.040
But it's exciting.

00:42:24.040 --> 00:42:25.210
Because then, we've gotten
all these letters

00:42:25.210 --> 00:42:26.980
from very young kids.

00:42:26.980 --> 00:42:29.900
A Monte Carlo simulation is a
very simple thing, actually.

00:42:29.900 --> 00:42:32.410
And immediately, it started
sparking their imagination

00:42:32.410 --> 00:42:33.700
about a million different
things.

00:42:33.700 --> 00:42:35.680
There's so much sports
statistics out there.

00:42:35.680 --> 00:42:36.900
You could leverage those
sports statistics.

00:42:36.900 --> 00:42:40.710
And now that you have a pretty
easy-to-use coding platform to

00:42:40.710 --> 00:42:43.050
do some really, really
interesting kind decision

00:42:43.050 --> 00:42:45.530
analysis, and frankly, stuff
that I don't think even some

00:42:45.530 --> 00:42:48.260
of the people in the head
offices of some of the sports

00:42:48.260 --> 00:42:49.380
teams have actually done.

00:42:49.380 --> 00:42:51.020
ERIC SCHMIDT: Go ahead.

00:42:51.020 --> 00:42:54.390
AUDIENCE: So you've done some
amazing things helping people

00:42:54.390 --> 00:42:55.710
actually learn stuff.

00:42:55.710 --> 00:42:57.520
And that's mostly
what schools do.

00:42:57.520 --> 00:42:59.810
But they do one other thing
that's important, which is

00:42:59.810 --> 00:43:02.870
they certify that this person
has a reasonable knowledge of

00:43:02.870 --> 00:43:03.810
this topic.

00:43:03.810 --> 00:43:07.530
I was wondering if you had
an thoughts on fixing or

00:43:07.530 --> 00:43:10.730
improving the system of
standardized testing.

00:43:10.730 --> 00:43:11.970
SALMAN KHAN: Yeah.

00:43:11.970 --> 00:43:13.800
Really, what you're talking
about is credentialing.

00:43:13.800 --> 00:43:15.980
How do people prove to the world
that they've learned

00:43:15.980 --> 00:43:17.910
something now that there are all
these great resources to

00:43:17.910 --> 00:43:19.030
actually learn?

00:43:19.030 --> 00:43:21.680
And I think there's a bunch of
interesting things here.

00:43:21.680 --> 00:43:22.840
I mean there's a big movement.

00:43:22.840 --> 00:43:24.310
And a lot of these things have
always been out there.

00:43:24.310 --> 00:43:25.270
People have talked about it.

00:43:25.270 --> 00:43:27.280
But now, there seems to
be some traction.

00:43:27.280 --> 00:43:29.360
It's generally called
competency-based learning,

00:43:29.360 --> 00:43:31.290
instead of it being based
literally on seat time.

00:43:31.290 --> 00:43:32.340
And then, you just
get promoted.

00:43:32.340 --> 00:43:33.540
Look, you can take as
long as you need.

00:43:33.540 --> 00:43:34.590
And when you feel you're
ready, you go

00:43:34.590 --> 00:43:36.170
take a proctored exam.

00:43:36.170 --> 00:43:37.130
It should be a rich exam.

00:43:37.130 --> 00:43:38.350
It could be even an oral exam.

00:43:38.350 --> 00:43:40.440
And you prove that you
actually know it.

00:43:40.440 --> 00:43:42.560
And I frankly think that's
going to be especially

00:43:42.560 --> 00:43:45.630
powerful at the higher
education level.

00:43:45.630 --> 00:43:47.840
And one thing that I'm
particularly excited about--

00:43:47.840 --> 00:43:50.800
and I'd be interested in
collaborating with any of you

00:43:50.800 --> 00:43:52.850
all that want to work on
something like this--

00:43:52.850 --> 00:43:55.590
I think computer sciences
is actually the

00:43:55.590 --> 00:43:56.650
ripest fruit there.

00:43:56.650 --> 00:43:59.880
Because we hire on a much
smaller scale than you guys.

00:43:59.880 --> 00:44:02.130
But we are also looking
for incredible people.

00:44:02.130 --> 00:44:09.330
And when we look GPAs, great
universities, it's a filter.

00:44:09.330 --> 00:44:11.210
And we probably have a lot
of false negatives.

00:44:11.210 --> 00:44:12.670
There's a lot of great people.

00:44:12.670 --> 00:44:15.600
John Resig, he's the world's
most known JavaScript

00:44:15.600 --> 00:44:17.950
programmer, wrote jQuery.

00:44:17.950 --> 00:44:20.810
In his cover letter, he
literally wrote I started

00:44:20.810 --> 00:44:22.090
jQuery project or whatever.

00:44:22.090 --> 00:44:23.650
And I was like, I guess we
should interview him.

00:44:26.290 --> 00:44:27.260
But later, I asked him.

00:44:27.260 --> 00:44:28.360
I said, where did you
go to school?

00:44:28.360 --> 00:44:28.865
He said, Rochester.

00:44:28.865 --> 00:44:30.420
I said, oh, that's
a good school.

00:44:30.420 --> 00:44:32.070
But what was your GPA?

00:44:32.070 --> 00:44:34.520
1.9.

00:44:34.520 --> 00:44:36.060
ERIC SCHMIDT: He was too busy
programming in JavaScript.

00:44:36.060 --> 00:44:36.840
SALMAN KHAN: It might
have been 2.0.

00:44:36.840 --> 00:44:37.370
Don't quote me.

00:44:37.370 --> 00:44:39.310
I think it was 1.9 or 2.0.

00:44:39.310 --> 00:44:40.320
It might have been a
little bit higher.

00:44:40.320 --> 00:44:44.590
But it was not a resume that
would typically make the cut

00:44:44.590 --> 00:44:46.550
at a Google or Khan Academy.

00:44:50.040 --> 00:44:53.360
But it pointed to me what's
wrong with our process.

00:44:53.360 --> 00:44:55.680
He's an off-the-charts brilliant
guy, fun to work

00:44:55.680 --> 00:44:57.650
with, everything.

00:44:57.650 --> 00:44:58.580
What happened?

00:44:58.580 --> 00:45:01.310
He said, well, I was
working on jQuery.

00:45:01.310 --> 00:45:03.410
And so we're missing those
people, unless they do

00:45:03.410 --> 00:45:05.170
something really
off-the-charts,

00:45:05.170 --> 00:45:06.310
like what he did.

00:45:06.310 --> 00:45:09.900
And so I think there should
be independent processes.

00:45:09.900 --> 00:45:11.590
And then, when you go and
actually get an interview

00:45:11.590 --> 00:45:13.500
here, we all make you go to
the whiteboard and write

00:45:13.500 --> 00:45:14.310
bubble sort.

00:45:14.310 --> 00:45:16.260
Or how to do sort this?

00:45:16.260 --> 00:45:18.820
Or how do you find the edge of
this boundary or whatever.

00:45:18.820 --> 00:45:19.880
And it's inconsistent.

00:45:19.880 --> 00:45:20.410
Some are hard.

00:45:20.410 --> 00:45:21.140
And some are easy.

00:45:21.140 --> 00:45:22.900
There might be some great people
who just having anxiety

00:45:22.900 --> 00:45:25.910
coding at a white board while
someone's watching them.

00:45:25.910 --> 00:45:28.660
And so I think there is
something that could be done

00:45:28.660 --> 00:45:31.930
where people go take maybe
a proctored, or at least

00:45:31.930 --> 00:45:34.750
authenticated, series
of challenges.

00:45:34.750 --> 00:45:38.690
And that's used as really a
credential or a filter, for

00:45:38.690 --> 00:45:40.260
people like us to see
where talent is.

00:45:40.260 --> 00:45:41.714
ERIC SCHMIDT: Did you
have a question?

00:45:41.714 --> 00:45:43.280
AUDIENCE: Hi, Sal.

00:45:43.280 --> 00:45:44.950
Thanks for everything you do.

00:45:44.950 --> 00:45:48.210
So at Google, we get to work
with a lot of great teachers

00:45:48.210 --> 00:45:50.960
who are forward-thinking and not
afraid of your model, not

00:45:50.960 --> 00:45:53.110
afraid of employing the flipped
classroom and being

00:45:53.110 --> 00:45:54.990
more of a guide on the side.

00:45:54.990 --> 00:45:58.040
But there are a ton of teachers
who are afraid of

00:45:58.040 --> 00:45:58.590
what you're doing.

00:45:58.590 --> 00:46:01.410
They feel like if this happens,
they're all going to

00:46:01.410 --> 00:46:03.010
take away our jobs.

00:46:03.010 --> 00:46:04.940
And they're the gate keepers
to the kids.

00:46:04.940 --> 00:46:06.640
So how do you reach
those teachers?

00:46:06.640 --> 00:46:09.165
And how do you reach, by
extension, those kids?

00:46:09.165 --> 00:46:12.740
SALMAN KHAN: I think the main
point is kind of-- actually,

00:46:12.740 --> 00:46:17.730
that was one of the main hopes
of this book, to make it clear

00:46:17.730 --> 00:46:19.780
that it's not about--

00:46:19.780 --> 00:46:22.890
because, as was talked about
before, teaching was viewed as

00:46:22.890 --> 00:46:24.320
a performance art before.

00:46:24.320 --> 00:46:28.220
And so it was kind of ingrained
in people that's

00:46:28.220 --> 00:46:29.670
where the value was.

00:46:29.670 --> 00:46:32.890
And to kind of, I think, get
more people thinking in this

00:46:32.890 --> 00:46:35.090
direction is for everyone
to realize that isn't

00:46:35.090 --> 00:46:35.940
where the value is.

00:46:35.940 --> 00:46:36.910
And this isn't just
lip service.

00:46:36.910 --> 00:46:40.420
The value really is on working
deeply with students,

00:46:40.420 --> 00:46:42.520
mentoring them, forming
connections with them.

00:46:42.520 --> 00:46:45.240
And I think when you phrase
it that way, most

00:46:45.240 --> 00:46:46.040
teachers really get it.

00:46:46.040 --> 00:46:49.580
And whenever I talk to people,
this isn't an assault on you.

00:46:49.580 --> 00:46:52.360
I think, unfortunately, most
of the public debate is an

00:46:52.360 --> 00:46:53.420
assault on teachers.

00:46:53.420 --> 00:46:54.830
And they group them
all together.

00:46:54.830 --> 00:46:57.400
And they make all sorts of
sweeping statements.

00:46:57.400 --> 00:46:59.120
This is an assault on a
system that has been

00:46:59.120 --> 00:47:00.310
constraining you.

00:47:00.310 --> 00:47:02.340
It's whenever people
get worried.

00:47:02.340 --> 00:47:05.510
The US is right behind Estonia
when it comes to factoring

00:47:05.510 --> 00:47:06.210
polynomials.

00:47:06.210 --> 00:47:09.310
All going to fall apart now.

00:47:09.310 --> 00:47:12.620
The reaction from government
is, let's put

00:47:12.620 --> 00:47:14.260
more tests on it.

00:47:14.260 --> 00:47:17.290
And there is a rationale
to that.

00:47:17.290 --> 00:47:20.230
And it might de-risk some
of the worst performing

00:47:20.230 --> 00:47:20.900
situations.

00:47:20.900 --> 00:47:23.880
But it also completely handicaps
everyone else.

00:47:23.880 --> 00:47:26.560
And it makes our system,
frankly, more Prussian.

00:47:26.560 --> 00:47:29.800
It makes it more rigid,
more controlled.

00:47:29.800 --> 00:47:31.700
And everything that we're trying
to promote-- and this

00:47:31.700 --> 00:47:32.770
is what I tell every teacher.

00:47:32.770 --> 00:47:34.540
And I think when they understand
that, they get

00:47:34.540 --> 00:47:35.830
really excited about it.

00:47:35.830 --> 00:47:39.000
It's about going back to the
teacher really being able to

00:47:39.000 --> 00:47:41.970
define the experience in really
interesting, creative

00:47:41.970 --> 00:47:44.780
ways but have tools that make
sure that the academic rigor

00:47:44.780 --> 00:47:45.620
is still being achieved.

00:47:45.620 --> 00:47:47.570
You know, when I was a tutoring
my cousins, this is

00:47:47.570 --> 00:47:48.060
what I wanted.

00:47:48.060 --> 00:47:49.970
There's all sorts of fun stuff
I want to do with my cousins.

00:47:49.970 --> 00:47:52.020
I want to teach them about
a Monte Carlo simulation.

00:47:52.020 --> 00:47:54.450
But at the same time, I also
want to make sure that they're

00:47:54.450 --> 00:47:56.130
reaching certain achievement
goals.

00:47:56.130 --> 00:47:59.800
And so I can keep track of
that asynchronously.

00:47:59.800 --> 00:48:01.570
I can manage the chaos
so to speak.

00:48:01.570 --> 00:48:04.460
ERIC SCHMIDT: Yes, sir.

00:48:04.460 --> 00:48:05.300
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:48:05.300 --> 00:48:06.480
This is inspiring.

00:48:06.480 --> 00:48:11.200
And it's inspiring to the extent
that I've taken on a

00:48:11.200 --> 00:48:13.740
challenge to really change the
way that I do a little bit of

00:48:13.740 --> 00:48:14.890
my own teaching.

00:48:14.890 --> 00:48:17.480
I have taught a citizen
schools class,

00:48:17.480 --> 00:48:19.380
for some time now--

00:48:19.380 --> 00:48:21.740
since before I got to
Google, actually--

00:48:21.740 --> 00:48:26.490
trying to teach sixth graders
computer science and algebra

00:48:26.490 --> 00:48:27.920
at the same time, since the

00:48:27.920 --> 00:48:29.470
fundamentals are really together.

00:48:29.470 --> 00:48:30.390
SALMAN KHAN: There's some good
tools for that now, too.

00:48:30.390 --> 00:48:32.700
AUDIENCE: Really very core--

00:48:32.700 --> 00:48:37.190
And in particular, to try to
motivate them with gaming

00:48:37.190 --> 00:48:39.190
context, creating video games.

00:48:39.190 --> 00:48:44.180
The challenge that I have,
that's not so much like the

00:48:44.180 --> 00:48:47.380
normal classroom challenge, is
the kids have to be really

00:48:47.380 --> 00:48:48.570
motivated on their own.

00:48:48.570 --> 00:48:49.580
Because there's no credit.

00:48:49.580 --> 00:48:50.440
There's no nothing.

00:48:50.440 --> 00:48:52.030
This is an after school
activity.

00:48:52.030 --> 00:48:55.110
If they're going to watch
anything at home, they have to

00:48:55.110 --> 00:48:56.530
do it because they want to.

00:48:56.530 --> 00:48:59.500
And two is I don't know that
some of these kids from the

00:48:59.500 --> 00:49:04.530
Bronx have tools at home with
which to go and view videos,

00:49:04.530 --> 00:49:09.580
to go and play with the
computers, et cetera.

00:49:09.580 --> 00:49:12.530
One, I'd like to sort of ask
your advice on those kinds of

00:49:12.530 --> 00:49:13.040
challenges.

00:49:13.040 --> 00:49:15.720
But also I'd like to ask your
advice really on just how to

00:49:15.720 --> 00:49:18.280
prepare videos that are
that engaging for

00:49:18.280 --> 00:49:20.450
a sixth grade audience.

00:49:20.450 --> 00:49:22.790
What are the things I should
be paying attention to?

00:49:22.790 --> 00:49:24.530
SALMAN KHAN: I'll
take the first.

00:49:24.530 --> 00:49:27.410
In terms of access issues,
that's a real issue.

00:49:27.410 --> 00:49:30.360
There has even been a few
charter schools where the

00:49:30.360 --> 00:49:33.710
school was able to get
laptops or computing

00:49:33.710 --> 00:49:35.030
devices to the students.

00:49:35.030 --> 00:49:37.220
But then, they get beat up on
the way home and someone takes

00:49:37.220 --> 00:49:38.880
it from them.

00:49:38.880 --> 00:49:44.250
And so the near-term solution
seems to be keep the school

00:49:44.250 --> 00:49:46.500
open a little bit longer, have
a computer lab, partner with

00:49:46.500 --> 00:49:47.920
the Boys &amp; Girls Club,
someplace where

00:49:47.920 --> 00:49:49.740
they can access it.

00:49:49.740 --> 00:49:51.970
I mean, which is essentially
saying it's actually hard for

00:49:51.970 --> 00:49:53.440
them to be able to access
it at home.

00:49:53.440 --> 00:49:53.950
But that's OK.

00:49:53.950 --> 00:49:54.750
They're accessing it.

00:49:54.750 --> 00:49:56.230
And actually, that serves
a double purpose.

00:49:56.230 --> 00:49:57.210
And I write a lot about that.

00:49:57.210 --> 00:49:59.020
It's crazy that school
ends two hours before

00:49:59.020 --> 00:50:00.720
parents come home.

00:50:00.720 --> 00:50:03.880
